cular state in the context of contemporary Asia and investigates whether there existed before modernity antecedents to the condition of secularity, understood as the differentiation of the sphere of the religious from other spheres of social life. The chapters presented in this book examine this issue in national contexts by looking at the historical formation of lexicons that defined the "secular", the "secular state," and "secularism". This approach requires paying attention to modern vernacular languages and their precedents in written traditions with often a very long tradition. This book presents three interpretive frameworks: multiple modernities, variety of secularisms, and typologies of post-colonial secular states.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aSecularismzAsia. 4aAsien. 4aKonolialismus. 4aLaizität. 4aReligion.  aAsian modernities.  aAsian religions.  aLaïcité.  acolonial encounter.1 aBaubérot, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdeaux, Pascal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourdeaux, Pascal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDufourmont, Eddy , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDufourmont, Eddy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEven, Marie-Dominique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaliberté, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaliberté, André, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMadinier, Rémy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadinier, Rémy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMohammad-Arif, Aminah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g